'''Neil Thomas''' [[Member of the British Empire|MBE]] (born 6 April 1968) is an English [[artistic gymnast]] who experienced most of his success in the [[Floor (gymnastics)|floor exercises]]. He is an inspiration to many young British gymnasts and the most successful British gymnast to date.

Winner of three gold medals spanning two [[Commonwealth Games]], Thomas also added a world silver medal on the floor in 1993, 1994 as well as finishing 20th at the [Barcelona Olympics].

He won a Commonwealth gold medal on floor at Auckland and the vault bronze medal at [[European Men's Artistic Gymnastics Championships|European Championships]] in 1990. In 1993 he won the UK<U+2019>s first World Championship medal in [[Artistic Gymnastics]] (silver)
1993.  A year later he won a gold medal on floor and became All-around champion and also won the silver medal on floor at [[World Championships]] in Brisbane.<ref>[http://www.british-gymnastics.org/site/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=135&Itemid=343] British Gymnastics official website.  Accessed December 4, 2009</ref>

Neil Thomas now works as a development officer in the north west of England.<ref>[http://m2002.thecgf.com/Sports/Gymnastics/Heroes/default.asp] Mamchester 2002 official website.  Accessed December 4, 2009</ref>

He was awarded the [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the 1995 New Year Honours for services to gymnastics and in recognition of his near single-handed achievement in putting British men's gymnastics on the map.<ref>Shropshire Star front page. December 31, 1994</ref>

